    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-04-12T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-04-12T14:00:00-05:00" n="948"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d948">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/16566: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-12T14:00:00-05:00"
                            >April 12, 1941—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>227. Kunming’s 8, April 9, 10 a.m.<note n="27" xml:id="d948fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> Please bring emphatically to the attention of the Japanese
                    Foreign Office in such manner as you may deem appropriate the endangering of
                    American lives by this indiscriminate bombing of Kunming. In so doing you may
                    wish to point out that American citizens, including American officials, reside
                    in that city for the purpose of carrying on legitimate activities and are
                    entitled to reside there without danger of attack by Japanese air forces. You
                    may care also to refer to the fact that the lives of American citizens continue
                    to be jeopardized and American citizens continue to suffer loss from such
                    bombings notwithstanding the fact that in most cases the Japanese authorities
                    have been given detailed information with regard to the location of American
                    property and the residences of American citizens.<note n="28" xml:id="d948fn2"
                        >For note dated April 14 sent by the Embassy in Japan to the Japanese
                        Foreign Office, see <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_710">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 710</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sent to Tokyo via Shanghai. Repeated to Chungking, Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
